&quot;SEE&quot; stands for &quot;Signed [or, evidently, Signing] Exact English&quot;. I
wouldn't say it's a pidgin. Its vocabulary is based on ASL's, but it
supplements them, and many signs are modified to incorporate a hand
shape corresponding with the first letter of the word in English. Unlike
ASL, it uses English word order, and explicitly translates English words
for which ASL would ordinarily omit the equivalent sign, such as forms
of &quot;to be&quot;, and uses prepositions where ASL would use spatial
positioning of signs to show the relative location of the things they
refer to. It also includes signs, IIRC, used as counterparts to certain
English inflections.
