Klingon, Esperanto and Lojban etc are not natural languages.  To
conflate the natural and artificial languages you just gloss over the
difference between the process by which some linguist (amateur or
otherwise) makes up a language out of whole cloth and the
extraordinarily social process by which language develops (and we just
don't know about the very earliest moments of that process).  If you
want to say that what Zamenhof and Okrand have done is anything like
what goes on in the long process of unplanned and undirected
development of natural languages then I don't think you'll understand
either process in the end.

