What an infant does when its environment contains only imperfect,
incomplete input (typically a pidgin) is create a creole, and creoles
have typical features that presumably represent the features of human
language &quot;out of the box&quot; without any of the idiosyncrasies of
existing languages.

(The reason the child of immigrants to, say, the US whose parents
speak only heavily accented English doesn't speak accented English is
that the child is surrounded by an environment of native speakers,
which becomes the primary input into its language acquisition process.
Presumably there is no significant Esperanto-speaking environment for
the child to grow up in.)

