Children usually get to understand their parent's way of speaking (if
they are not adopted), but the speech of other children is more
important for the way they choose to express themselves. Children
often do not learn to speak language the way their parents do, even if
they understand each other.

You can't assume that there are different languages, just because
Human language is diverse enough to be mutually incomprehensible at
times. At first glance, it looks as if there are lots of different
languages on Earth, but if &quot;looks as if&quot; is a good argument, then the
Earth is flat.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Did they then reach out to share a more natural Esperanto?
&gt; That could certainly happen, but there doesn't
&gt; seem to be a record of it.  I don't know why.  Others known to use
&gt; Esperanto, not  denaskuloj at all, have in their tiny, perhaps
&gt; diminishing, worldwide numbers continued to polish it.  (They polish
&gt; it; I just sort of smudge it.)
">

What does it mean to &quot;polish a language&quot;? It it what Shakespeare did
to English and Goethe to German? In that case the creation of artistic
works proceeds by exploring the potentials of Human language, not by
creating language.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Esperanto is artificial (as ASL, by the way, emphatically is not). But
&gt; all language is to some extent artificial and to some extent natural.
&gt; Anything distinctive that I do with language, in any language, is
&gt; artificial in the sense that one identifiable person has done it.
">

No, it's usually not defined that way. Natural language is part of any
sane person, whether or not his specific ways of using it has been
described. Artificial languages (note the plural) must be described
before they can be used, and they are used for other purposes than
natural language (note the singular). Esperanto is a specific way of
using Human language, and so is ASL. There might be two closely
related natural languages, spoken and signed, but it's safer to assume
that they are essentially the same in the brain and only diverge at
spell-out.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; And anyone who purports to invent an artificial language is only
&gt; building on the inherited human ability to make language.
">

A normal Homo sapiens does not have the ability to live _without_
language. He doesn't make it, he is born with it and may use his time
exploring it deeper than biology demands. You cannot really make a
distinction between a dialect of Human and the other things that the
speakers of that dialect have in common.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; That's why Esperanto
&gt; seems so familiar to those who learn it, especially to speakers of
&gt; Indo-European languages.  It's just a language, with to be sure an
&gt; unusual history and unusual claims attached to it.
">

It's less than a language, it's one name for language among thousands.
And it's more than language; Esperanto is like all other speech
communities in actually _being_ its history and the claims and customs
that go with it. If you reduce Esperanto (or English, Irish or
whatever) to the pure language part, then nothing specific remains;
only the Human language is left. On the other hand, if you want to add
anything specific in order to delimit Esperanto (or English, Irish...)
from other languages, then something non-linguistic will inevitably
creep in.

Jens S. Larsen
